		on Wednesday December 18, 2024 @08:51AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23554985&amp;cid=65022031">#65022031</a>)
		<small><a href="http://hyperlogos.org/" title="http://hyperlogos.org/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a>
<a href="//slashdot.org/~drinkypoo/journal/" title="Sunday September 17, 2023 @08:53AM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65022031"><p>I have a TP-Link router. I am not afraid of it because I have reflashed it with OpenWRT. A lot of their routers run Linux and are supported by OpenWRT.</p><p>Pretty much all consumer routers come from China so you don't really have a choice about where the hardware comes from. But you do have a choice about the software, if you look at the <a href="https://openwrt.org/toh/start" title="openwrt.org">OpenWRT ToH</a> [openwrt.org] before you buy. Buying a router which isn't supported by them is a very bad idea. Yes, there are some other distributions as well. Maybe you think one of them is better, you do you etc. But I want one well supported option and that's as close as you can get.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65022031">
